}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mishra, Sabyasachi}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Actors in Odia cinema]]\n[[Category:People from Odisha]]\n[[Category:Cinema of Odisha]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sabyasachi Mishra\n| native_name        = ''\u0b38\u0b2c\u0b4d\u0b5f\u0b38\u0b3e\u0b1a\u0b40 \u0b2e\u0b3f\u0b36\u0b4d\u0b30''\n| native_name_lang   = or\n| image              = Sabysachi Mishra P.JPG\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = Oct 6, 1985\n| birth_place        = [[Burla, India|Burla]], [[Odisha]], [[India]]\n| nationality        = [[India]]n\n| alma_mater         = [[ABIT]]\n| occupation         = [[Actor]], [[Model (people)|Model]], [[Playback Singer]]\n| height             = {{convert|5|ft|11|in|m}}\n| parents            = Surendra Prasad Mishra, IAS<br>Dr Susama Mishra, Writer\n| birthname          = Sabyasachi Mishra\n| yearsactive        = 2002\u20132007 As an Album Actor<br /> 2007 \u2013 Present as a Film Actor|\n}}\n'''Sabyasachi Mishra''' ({{lang-or|\u0b38\u0b2c\u0b4d\u0b5f\u0b38\u0b3e\u0b1a\u0b40 \u0b2e\u0b3f\u0b36\u0b4d\u0b30}}; born 6 October 1985) is an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[film actor]] known for his work in [[Oriya cinema|Odia Cinema]] and [[Telugu cinema]]. He has also marked his presence at West Bengal by Entering into [[Cinema of West Bengal|Bengali Cinema]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/bhubaneswar/sabyasachi-mishra-now-in-a-bengali-film/articleshow/65920986.cms|title=Sabyasachi Mishra now in a Bengali film - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> Sabyasachi Mishra has a large fan following in Odisha, referred as the '''''Superstar''''' of [[Cinema of Odisha|Ollywood]].<ref>{{cite web|author=TNN 19 Sep 2012, 12.00PM IST |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-09-19/news-interviews/33951977_1_sabyasachi-fans-hara-pattnaik |title=Sabyasachi connects well with fans - Times Of India |publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2012-09-19 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://incredibleorissa.com/oriyafilms/sabyasachi-mishra/ |title=Sabyasachi Mishra &#124; Biography, Actor Wiki, Film List, Oriya Hero Movies |publisher=Incredibleorissa.com |date=2011-11-26 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ollywoodone.com/blog/?p=655 |title=Sabyasachi: The all rounder in Ollywood &#124; Blog |publisher=Ollywoodone.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref> ''[[Pagala Premi]]'' was his first movie, for which he earned an [[Odisha State Film Awards]] for Best Actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/02/09/stories/2009020952330300.htm |title=Other States / Orissa News : Jayadev Puraskar for Pratihari |publisher=The Hindu |date=2009-02-09 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref> Sabyasachi got his second state award for ''[[Emiti Bi Prema Hue]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enewsinsight.com/odisha-insight/odisha-state-film-awards-sabyasachi-barsha-get-top-honours/|title=Odisha State Film Awards: Sabyasachi, Barsha get Top Honours - The News Insight|date=11 December 2013|publisher=|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref> He won the [[Filmfare Awards East]] as best actor for ''[[Mu Eka Tumara]]'' in 2013. He has completed Three Telugu movies and 36 Odia Movies till 2019.\nHis first two Telugu movies are, '''''Neerajanam''''' and '''''Sita Ramula Kallyanam chuthamu Raarandi'''''. His first Bengali Movie is '''''Raktomukhi Neela'''''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/Sabyasachi-Mishra|title=Sabyasachi Mishra: Movies, Photos, Videos, News, Biography & Birthday {{!}} eTimes|website=timesofindia.indiatimes.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\u21b5\n\nSabyasachi has lots of Brand Endorsements to his credit and he is considered as the Brand's favorite.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/odisha/sabyasachi-happy-to-spread-love-and-joy/cid/1458782|title=Sabyasachi 'Happy' to spread love and joy|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orissapost.com/herbal-holi-event-to-host-bollywood-celebs/|title=Herbal Holi event to host Bollywood celebs - OrissaPOST|date=2019-02-22|website=Odisha News, Odisha Latest news, Odisha Daily - OrissaPOST|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>He was selected as the brand ambassador for IPL team [[Deccan Chargers]], [[Odisha Tennis Premier League]], '''''Cricket For The Blind in India''''' etc to promote Sports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://orissadiary.com/amp/3rd-season-odisha-tennis-premier-league-otpl-kick-off-4th-december-2019/|title=3rd Season of Odisha Tennis Premier League (OTPL) to kick off from 4th December 2019|date=2019-11-02|website=OdishaDiary|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\nSabyasachi is also popular for his Social Works and contribution to society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mycitylinks.in/super-22-show-for-pwd-talents|title=Super 22 Show for PWD Talents|website=Mycitylinks- Bhubaneswar {{!}} Cuttack {{!}} Puri|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/odisha/2015/nov/14/Childrens-Festival-Anjali-from-Today-842838.html|title=Children's Festival 'Anjali' from Today|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2002\u20132007: Early career as an album actor===\nSabyasachi entered the entertainment world as a small screen actor for album songs. Director Saroj Satpathy introduced him in an album song for the program ''Rangarang'' of [[DD Oriya|Doordarshan Oriya(DD-6)]]. He acted in more than 0 music videos. During this period he has also acted in some Bhojpuri, Bengali, Chatishgadi and Panjabi Music videos.\n\n===2007\u20132009: Rise as a cine actor===\nFilm director [[Hara Patnaik]] spotted him performing in a stage show and offered him the movie ''[[Pagala Premi]]''. Hara Pattanaik is considered his godfather.<ref>{{cite web|author=Chandrima Maitra |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120405/jsp/odisha/story_15334786.jsp#.UjeGFsYwoXs |title=Lights, action, drama |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2012-04-05 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.click2odisha.com/sabyasachi.php |title=Sabyasachi Mishra, profile, Odia Actor, Classifieds, Yellow Pages |publisher=www.click2odisha.Com |date=1984-10-06 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref> [[Pagala Premi]] was released on 14 June 2007. His critically acclaimed roles included his anti-hero of ''[[Mu Sapanara Soudagar]]'', physically challenged character of Keun Duniaru Asila Bandhu.\n\n===2010 \u2013 present: Commercial stardom===\nIn the movie ''Mu Eka Tumara'', Sabyasachi played the character of a boy who can't speak, for which he bagged many awards including Filmfare award. His 2015 released movie ''[[Pilata Bigidigala]]'' was considered as one of the biggest blockbusters. The Sabyasachi starrer, 2016 March 18 released ''Hela Mate Prema Jara'' also got extraordinary response from public and critics. In 2018 \"Tokata Fasigala\" & in 2019 \"Mal Mahu Jiban Mati\" Brought Huge success for Sabya as blockbuster movies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://orissadiary.com/amp/mal-mahu-jiban-mati-becomes-first-odia-movie-officially-promoted-tiktok/|title=Mal Mahu Jiban Mati becomes the First Odia Movie to be Officially promoted on TikTok|date=2019-11-12|website=OdishaDiary|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> He also started singing and did the play back singing for both the title songs of \"Pilata Bigidigala\" and \"Hela Mate Prema Jara\". Both the songs were super hit. Recent song \"Maya re Baya\" by Sabyasachi went viral over social media, becoming a big craze among youth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/odisha/2018/jul/13/sabyasachi-turns-singer-yet-again-1842846.html|title=Sabyasachi turns singer yet again!|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> \n\nSabyasachi did his debut in South Indian Film industry with Telugu movie ''Neerajanam'' under the banner \"Mahalaxmi Movies\". His upcoming Telugu movie is \"Adi Oka Idile\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/adi-oka-idile-director-krish-launches-the-first-look-of-the-film/articleshow/64015104.cms|title=\u2018Adi Oka Idile\u2019: Director Krish launches the first look of the film - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Family===\nSabyasachi is born in to Surendra Prasad Mishra, an IAS officer and eminent writer and poet 'Dr Sushama Mishra'. His Father has also served the Indian Air force before joining as an administrative officer. His mother is a recipient of Ladli National Media award. He has a single brother Soumya Kanta Mishra who works as a Telecom Engineer.'He speaks fluently [[Odia language|Odia]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/meet-sabyasachi-mishra-the-half-telugu-odia-superstar/articleshow/57186332.cms|title=Meet Sabyasachi Mishra, the 'Half telugu' Odia superstar - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nSabyasachi is an Engineer who completed his B.Tech in Electronics and Telecom from the [[Silicon Institute of Technology]], which is a private college in Odisha. He was also placed in Infosys but later on left it so as to pursue his interest in film industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100804/jsp/orissa/story_12766558.jsp |title=The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) &#124; Orissa &#124; Tool room to screen test, actor rules |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2010-08-04 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* 2020 - Jete Gori Sete Story (Odia) (UPCOMING) waiting\n*2020 - Nadhir Dhinna (Tamil) (UPCOMING)\n*2020 - Adi Oka Idile (Telugu) (UPCOMING)\n*2019 - ''[[Raktomukhi Neela]]''(Bengali)\n* 2019 - ''[[Mall mahu jibana mati]]''\n* 2019 - ''[[Abhimana]]''\n* 2018 - ''[[4 Idiots]]''\n* 2018 - ''[[Tokata Fasigala]]''\n* 2017 \u2013 ''[[Sita Ramanka Bahaghara Kali Jugare]]''\n* 2017 \u2013 ''[[Sitaramula Kalyanam Chuthamu Raarandi]]'' (Telugu)\n* 2017 \u2013 ''[[Neerajanam]]'' (Telugu) \n* 2016 - ''[[Chhati Tale Ding Dong]]''\n* 2016 \u2013 ''[[Bye Bye Dubai]]''\n* 2016 \u2013 ''[[Hela Mate Prema Jara]]''\n* 2015 \u2013 ''[[Pilata Bigidigala]]''\n* 2014 \u2013 ''[[Smile Please (2014 film)|Smile Please]]''\n* 2013 \u2013 ''[[Mu Eka Tumara]]''\n* 2012 \u2013 ''[[Om Sai Ram]]''\n* 2012 \u2013 ''[[Kebe Tume Nahan Kebe Mu Nahin]]''\n* 2012 \u2013 ''[[Emiti Bi Prema Hue]]''\n* 2012 - ''[[Kemiti E Bandhana]]''\n* 2011 \u2013 ''[[Chandini, I Miss You]]''\n* 2011 \u2013 ''[[Dosti (2011 film)|Dosti]]''\n* 2011 \u2013 ''[[Chatire Lekhichi Tori Naa]]''\n* 2010 \u2013 ''[[Aakhi Palakare Tu]]''\n* 2010 \u2013 ''[[Dil Tate Deichi]]''\n* 2010 \u2013 ''[[Sasura Ghara Zindabad]]''\n* 2010 \u2013 ''[[Megha Sabari Re Asiba Pheri]]''\n* 2010 \u2013 ''[[Tora Mora Jodi Sundara]]''\n* 2009 \u2013 ''[[Prem Rogi]]'' (Guest appearance)\n* 2009 \u2013 ''[[Love Dot Com]]''\n* 2009 \u2013 ''[[Dream Girl (2009 film)|Dream Girl]]''\n* 2009 \u2013 ''[[Tu Mori Pain]]''\n* 2009 \u2013 ''[[Kou Duniaru Asila Bandhu]]''\n* 2009 \u2013 ''[[Pagala Karichi Paunji Tora]]''\n* 2009 \u2013 ''[[Dhire Dhire Prema Hela]]''\n* 2008 \u2013 ''[[Mate Ani Dela Lakhe Phaguna]]''\n* 2008 \u2013 ''[[Bande Utkala Janani (film)|Bande Utkala Janani]]''\n* 2008 \u2013 ''[[To Bina Bhala Lagena]]''\n* 2008 \u2013 ''[[Mu Sapanara Soudagar]]''\n* 2007 \u2013 ''[[Pagala Premi]]''\n\n==Awards==\n* [[Filmfare Awards East]], as Best Oriya Actor 2013 for ''[[Mu Eka Tumara]]''\n* [[Odisha State Film Awards]], as Best Actor 2012 for ''[[Emiti Bi Prema Hue]]''\n* [[Odisha State Film Awards]], as Best Actor 2007 for  ''[[Pagala Premi]]''{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n* Odia filmfare awards 2014 as Best Actor for ''[[Smile Please]]''\n* Tarang Cine Award 2015 as best actor for ''[[Smile Please]]''\n* Tarang Cine Awards 2016 as best actor  for ''[[Pilata Bigidi Gala]]''\n* Tarang Cine Utsav Award 2019 as Best Jodi with [[Elina Samantray]] for ''[[Tokata Fasigala]]''\n* Tarang Cine Utsav Award 2020 as ''Best Dramebaaz of the Year 2019''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sabyasachi Mishra}}\n* {{IMDb name|3372052}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mishra, Sabyasachi}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Actors in Odia cinema]]\n[[Category:People from Odisha]]\n[[Category:Cinema of Odisha]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Sabysanchi mishra", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sabyasachi_Mishra"}
{"title_page": "Stiletto heel", "text_new": "{{other uses2|Stiletto}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n[[File:White_stiletto_high-heels.jpg|300px|thumb|A shoe with a stiletto heel]]\n\nA '''stiletto heel''' is a long, thin, [[high heel]] found on some [[boot]]s and [[shoe]]s.\n\nIt is named after the [[stiletto]] dagger, the phrase being primarily recorded in the early 1930s.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.oed.com/bbcwords/stiletto-new.html|title= Stiletto|year= 2009|work= Oxford English Dictionary|publisher=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100413150534/http://oed.com/bbcwords/stiletto-new.html|archive-date=13 April 2010 |url-status=dead|access-date= 20 December 2012}}</ref> Stiletto heels may vary in length from 2.5 centimetres (1 inch) to 25&nbsp;cm (10 inches) or more if a platform sole is used, and are sometimes defined as having a diameter at the ground of less than 1&nbsp;cm (slightly less than half an inch). Stiletto-style heels {{convert|5|cm|abbr=on}} or shorter are called [[kitten heel]]s.\n\nNot all high slim heels merit the description stiletto. The extremely slender classic Italian-style stiletto heels of the late 1950s and very early 1960s were no more than {{convert|5|mm|abbr=on}} in diameter for much of their length, although the heel sometimes flared out a little at the top-piece (tip). After their demise in the mid-late 1960s, such slender heels were hard to find until recently due to changes in the way heels were mass-produced.\n\n==History==\n{{Further|Shoe fetishism}}\n{{More citations needed section|date=April 2019}}\n[[File:Stiefelwiki1e.jpg|190px|thumb|Stiletto heels can be found on almost every type of shoes, such as these ankle boots]]\n\nRelatively thin high heels were certainly around in the late 19th century, as numerous [[fetish art|fetish drawing]]s attest. Firm photographic evidence exists in the form of photographs of Parisian singer [[Mistinguett]] from the 1940s. These shoes were designed by [[Andre Perugia]], who began designing shoes in 1906. It seems unlikely that he invented the stiletto, but he is probably the first firmly-documented designer of the high, slim heel. The word stiletto applied to a heel is derived from a [[knife]] or [[dagger]] [[stiletto]], which is a long, thin blade, to which the heel of the shoe is similar in profile. Its usage in footwear first appeared in print in the ''[[New Statesman]]'' magazine in 1959: \"She came ...forward, her walk made lopsided by the absence of one heel of the stilettos\".<ref name=Games2007>{{Cite book|last = Games|first = Alex|year = 2007|title = Balderdash & Piffle: One Sandwich Short of a Dog's Dinner|isbn = 978-1-84607-235-2|publisher = BBC Books|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/balderdashpiffle0000game}}</ref>\n\nHigh-heel shoes were worn by men and women [[courtier]]s. The stiletto heel came with the advent of technology using a supporting metal shaft or stem embedded into the heel, instead of wood or other, weaker materials that required a wide heel. This revival of the opulent heel style can be attributed to the designer [[Roger Vivier]] and such designs became very popular in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.lifeinitaly.com/fashion/high-heels.asp|title= Italian Fashion: The History of High Heels|first= Meredith|last= Paslawsky|date= November 2008|publisher= Life In Italy|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151222104328/http://www.lifeinitaly.com/fashion/high-heels.asp|archivedate= 22 December 2015|accessdate= 20 December 2012|quote= In 1954, Roger Vivier designed the first stiletto heel with its infamous bold arch for the house of Dior. \"Stiletto\" is an Italian word for a small metal dagger.}}</ref>\n\nAs time went on, stiletto heels would become known more for their erotic nature than for their ability to make height. Stiletto heels are a common [[Sexual fetishism|fetish]] item. As a fashion item, their popularity has changed over time. After an initial wave of popularity in the 1950s, they reached their most refined shape in the early 1960s, when the toes of the shoes which bore them became as slender and elongated as the stiletto heels themselves. As a result of the overall sharpness of outline, it was customary for women to refer to the whole shoe as a \"stiletto\", not just the heel, via [[synecdoche]] (''[[pars pro toto]]''). Although they faded from the scene after the [[The Beatles|Beatle]] era began, their popularity continued at street level, and women stubbornly refused to give them up even after they could no longer readily find them in the mainstream shops. A version of the stiletto heel was reintroduced in 1974 by [[Manolo Blahnik]], who dubbed his \"new\" heel the \"Needle\". Similar heels were stocked at the big [[Biba]] store in London, by [[Russell & Bromley]] and by smaller boutiques. Old, unsold stocks of pointed-toe stilettos and contemporary efforts to replicate them (lacking the true stiletto heel because of changes in the way heels were by then being mass-produced) were sold in street fashion markets and became popular with [[Punk subculture|punks]] and with other fashion \"tribes\" of the late 1970s until supplies of the inspirational original styles dwindled in the early 1980s. Subsequently, round-toe shoes with slightly thicker (sometimes cone-shaped) semi-stiletto heels, often very high in an attempt to convey slenderness were frequently worn at the office with wide-shouldered [[Suit (clothing)|power suits]]. The style survived through much of the 1980s but almost completely disappeared during the 1990s, when professional and college-age women took to wearing shoes with thick, block heels. The slender stiletto heel staged a major comeback after 2000 when young women adopted the style for dressing up office wear or adding a feminine touch to casual wear, like jeans.{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nStiletto heels are particularly associated with the image of the ''[[femme fatale]]''. They are often considered to be a seductive item of clothing, and often feature in popular culture in this context.{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==Advantages==\nSome of the benefits of wearing stilettos and other high heels include; longer, sexier, hotter and more feminine legs, it boosts your self-confidence, it makes your legs look slimmer and longer while making you look taller and it helps to strengthen & work your foot, heel, calf, knee and thigh muscles. It even makes your foot look smaller. It makes you safer by being used as a standby weapon to protect from rapists and molesters. And of course if your man is having an affair, you have something ready to kick him with or throw at him.\n\nAdditionally, it makes you look more stylish and sexy when pairing up with tights, stockings or a pantyhose, it helps to enhance your body figure by lifting up your butt, flattening your stomach areas, accentuating you breasts and overall makes you look desirable. Last but certainly not least, it gains you more and special attention from males around. In fact, one of my friends always turns around when he sees a woman in stilettos, click-clacking past and stares at her receding figure in awe, admiration and desire.\n\nIt will help you in work, making you look more important and powerful like Yahoo!'s Marissa Mayer and Facebook's Sheryl Sandberg, and if your job involves public relations, men will be more polite and respectful. In fact a study proved that when woman where heels above 4\", men are willing to help them 3 times more than if they were wearing heels between 2\" and 4\" and 7 times more than if they were wearing heels below 2\" or flats.\n\n==Disadvantages==\nAll high heels counter the natural functionality of the foot, sometimes causing skeletal and muscular problems if users wear them excessively; such shoes are a common cause of [[venous]] complaints such as pain, fatigue, and heavy-feeling legs, and have been found to provoke [[venous hypertension]] in the lower limbs.<ref>{{cite journal|last= Wagner|first= T.F.|title= Influence of high-heeled shoes on venous function in young women|journal= Journal of Vascular Surgery|volume= 56|issue= 4|pages= 1039\u20131044|publisher= [[Society for Vascular Surgery]]|date= October 2012|url= http://www.jvascsurg.org/article/S0741-5214(12)00117-6/abstract|display-authors=etal|doi=10.1016/j.jvs.2012.01.039|doi-access= free}}</ref> Despite their impracticality and fluctuating demand, they persist as a fashion option.\n\nStiletto heels concentrate a large amount of force into a small area. The great pressure under such a heel can cause damage to carpets and floors.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last= Bergstein|first= Rachelle|title= Women from the Ankle Down \u2013 The Story of Shoes and How They Define Us|location= New York|publisher= [[Harper Collins]]|year= 2012|type= Hardback|isbn= 978-0-06-196961-4|pages= [https://archive.org/details/womenfromankledo00berg/page/284 284]|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/womenfromankledo00berg/page/284}}\n{{High heels|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stiletto Heel}}\n[[Category:High-heeled footwear]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses2|Stiletto}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n[[File:White_stiletto_high-heels.jpg|300px|thumb|A shoe with a stiletto heel]]\n\nA '''stiletto heel''' is a long, thin, [[high heel]] found on some [[boot]]s and [[shoe]]s.\n\nIt is named after the [[stiletto]] dagger, the phrase being primarily recorded in the early 1930s.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.oed.com/bbcwords/stiletto-new.html|title= Stiletto|year= 2009|work= Oxford English Dictionary|publisher=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100413150534/http://oed.com/bbcwords/stiletto-new.html|archive-date=13 April 2010 |url-status=dead|access-date= 20 December 2012}}</ref> Stiletto heels may vary in length from 2.5 centimetres (1 inch) to 25&nbsp;cm (10 inches) or more if a platform sole is used, and are sometimes defined as having a diameter at the ground of less than 1&nbsp;cm (slightly less than half an inch). Stiletto-style heels {{convert|5|cm|abbr=on}} or shorter are called [[kitten heel]]s.\n\nNot all high slim heels merit the description stiletto. The extremely slender classic Italian-style stiletto heels of the late 1950s and very early 1960s were no more than {{convert|5|mm|abbr=on}} in diameter for much of their length, although the heel sometimes flared out a little at the top-piece (tip). After their demise in the mid-late 1960s, such slender heels were hard to find until recently due to changes in the way heels were mass-produced.\n\n==History==\n{{Further|Shoe fetishism}}\n{{More citations needed section|date=April 2019}}\n[[File:Stiefelwiki1e.jpg|190px|thumb|Stiletto heels can be found on almost every type of shoes, such as these ankle boots]]\n\nRelatively thin high heels were certainly around in the late 19th century, as numerous [[fetish art|fetish drawing]]s attest. Firm photographic evidence exists in the form of photographs of Parisian singer [[Mistinguett]] from the 1940s. These shoes were designed by [[Andre Perugia]], who began designing shoes in 1906. It seems unlikely that he invented the stiletto, but he is probably the first firmly-documented designer of the high, slim heel. The word stiletto applied to a heel is derived from a [[knife]] or [[dagger]] [[stiletto]], which is a long, thin blade, to which the heel of the shoe is similar in profile. Its usage in footwear first appeared in print in the ''[[New Statesman]]'' magazine in 1959: \"She came ...forward, her walk made lopsided by the absence of one heel of the stilettos\".<ref name=Games2007>{{Cite book|last = Games|first = Alex|year = 2007|title = Balderdash & Piffle: One Sandwich Short of a Dog's Dinner|isbn = 978-1-84607-235-2|publisher = BBC Books|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/balderdashpiffle0000game}}</ref>\n\nHigh-heel shoes were worn by men and women [[courtier]]s. The stiletto heel came with the advent of technology using a supporting metal shaft or stem embedded into the heel, instead of wood or other, weaker materials that required a wide heel. This revival of the opulent heel style can be attributed to the designer [[Roger Vivier]] and such designs became very popular in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.lifeinitaly.com/fashion/high-heels.asp|title= Italian Fashion: The History of High Heels|first= Meredith|last= Paslawsky|date= November 2008|publisher= Life In Italy|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151222104328/http://www.lifeinitaly.com/fashion/high-heels.asp|archivedate= 22 December 2015|accessdate= 20 December 2012|quote= In 1954, Roger Vivier designed the first stiletto heel with its infamous bold arch for the house of Dior. \"Stiletto\" is an Italian word for a small metal dagger.}}</ref>\n\nAs time went on, stiletto heels would become known more for their erotic nature than for their ability to make height. Stiletto heels are a common [[Sexual fetishism|fetish]] item. As a fashion item, their popularity has changed over time. After an initial wave of popularity in the 1950s, they reached their most refined shape in the early 1960s, when the toes of the shoes which bore them became as slender and elongated as the stiletto heels themselves. As a result of the overall sharpness of outline, it was customary for women to refer to the whole shoe as a \"stiletto\", not just the heel, via [[synecdoche]] (''[[pars pro toto]]''). Although they faded from the scene after the [[The Beatles|Beatle]] era began, their popularity continued at street level, and women stubbornly refused to give them up even after they could no longer readily find them in the mainstream shops. A version of the stiletto heel was reintroduced in 1974 by [[Manolo Blahnik]], who dubbed his \"new\" heel the \"Needle\". Similar heels were stocked at the big [[Biba]] store in London, by [[Russell & Bromley]] and by smaller boutiques. Old, unsold stocks of pointed-toe stilettos and contemporary efforts to replicate them (lacking the true stiletto heel because of changes in the way heels were by then being mass-produced) were sold in street fashion markets and became popular with [[Punk subculture|punks]] and with other fashion \"tribes\" of the late 1970s until supplies of the inspirational original styles dwindled in the early 1980s. Subsequently, round-toe shoes with slightly thicker (sometimes cone-shaped) semi-stiletto heels, often very high in an attempt to convey slenderness were frequently worn at the office with wide-shouldered [[Suit (clothing)|power suits]]. The style survived through much of the 1980s but almost completely disappeared during the 1990s, when professional and college-age women took to wearing shoes with thick, block heels. The slender stiletto heel staged a major comeback after 2000 when young women adopted the style for dressing up office wear or adding a feminine touch to casual wear, like jeans.{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nStiletto heels are particularly associated with the image of the ''[[femme fatale]]''. They are often considered to be a seductive item of clothing, and often feature in popular culture in this context.{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==Image==\nStilettos, like all similar [[high-heeled shoe]]s, give the optical illusion of a longer, slimmer leg, a smaller foot, and overall greater height. They alter the wearer's posture and gait,<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/bering-in-mind/2014/07/23/the-high-heel-hottie-effect-the-evolutionary-psychology-of-womens-shoes/|title= The High-Heel Hottie Effect: The Evolutionary Psychology of Women\u2019s Shoes|first= Jesse|last= Bering|date= 23 July 2014|magazine= [[Scientific American]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150126022304/http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/bering-in-mind/2014/07/23/the-high-heel-hottie-effect-the-evolutionary-psychology-of-womens-shoes/|archive-date=26 January 2015 |url-status= live|quote= By exaggerating the normal female gait, high heels serve to falsely enhance our perception of the wearer\u2019s femininity.}}</ref> flexing the calf muscles and making the bust and buttocks more prominent.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/oct/28/fashion|title= Are we just masochists?|first= Hannah|last= Betts|date= 27 October 2008|newspaper= [[The Guardian]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150126023553/http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/oct/28/fashion|archive-date=26 January 2015 |url-status= live|quote= Heels alter the angle of the buttocks by 20 or 30 degrees to create a more youthful and thus fertile-looking body.}}</ref>\n\n==Disadvantages==\nAll high heels counter the natural functionality of the foot, sometimes causing skeletal and muscular problems if users wear them excessively; such shoes are a common cause of [[venous]] complaints such as pain, fatigue, and heavy-feeling legs, and have been found to provoke [[venous hypertension]] in the lower limbs.<ref>{{cite journal|last= Wagner|first= T.F.|title= Influence of high-heeled shoes on venous function in young women|journal= Journal of Vascular Surgery|volume= 56|issue= 4|pages= 1039\u20131044|publisher= [[Society for Vascular Surgery]]|date= October 2012|url= http://www.jvascsurg.org/article/S0741-5214(12)00117-6/abstract|display-authors=etal|doi=10.1016/j.jvs.2012.01.039|doi-access= free}}</ref> Despite their impracticality and fluctuating demand, they persist as a fashion option.\n\nStiletto heels concentrate a large amount of force into a small area. The great pressure under such a heel can cause damage to carpets and floors.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last= Bergstein|first= Rachelle|title= Women from the Ankle Down \u2013 The Story of Shoes and How They Define Us|location= New York|publisher= [[Harper Collins]]|year= 2012|type= Hardback|isbn= 978-0-06