{"title_page": "Henry of Oyta", "text_new": "{{short description|German theologian and philosopher}}\n'''Henry of Oyta''' ({{lang-de|Heinrich Totting von Oyta}}) (c.1330 \u2013 1397) was a German theologian and [[nominalist]] philosopher.\n\n==Life==\nHe was born at [[Friesoythe]] in [[Lower Saxony]].<ref>{{in lang|de}} [http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz29313.html deutsche-biographie.de, ''Heinrich Totting von Oyta''.]</ref>  \nHenry graduated M.A. at the [[Charles University in Prague|University of Prague]] in 1355. He was then rector of a school in [[Erfurt]], and returned to Prague in 1366.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mordechai Feingold|title=History of Universities: Volume XXI/1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=anGQ4QTBCX0C&pg=PA212|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=20 July 2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-929738-2|page=212}}</ref> In the course of a long-running dispute, Adalbert Ranconis accused him of heresy in 1369\u201370.<ref>{{cite book|author=Stefan Swie\u017cawski|title=Les tribulations de l'eccl\u00e9siologie \u00e0 la fin du Moyen Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fUPIAwgkLfwC&pg=PA17|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1997|publisher=Editions Beauchesne|isbn=978-2-7010-1351-0|page=17 note 64|language=fr}}</ref> He began teaching at the [[University of Paris]] in 1377.<ref name=\"Meyjes1999\">{{cite book|author=Guillaume Henri Marie Posthumus Meyjes|title=Jean Gerson, Apostle of Unity: His Church Politics and Ecclesiology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=64h0Y-lLB7AC&pg=PA323|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1999|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-11296-4|page=323}}</ref> For reasons connected with the [[Western Schism]], he left Paris in 1381;<ref>{{cite book|author=Guillaume Henri Marie Posthumus Meyjes|title=Jean Gerson, Apostle of Unity: His Church Politics and Ecclesiology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=64h0Y-lLB7AC&pg=PA22|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1999|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-11296-4|page=22}}</ref> he then taught at Prague, 1381 to 1381, lecturing there on the [[Psalms]] and [[Gospel of John]].<ref name=\"Meyjes1999\"/><ref>{{cite book|author1=Bernard McGinn|author2=John Meyendorff|title=Christian Spirituality: High Middle Ages and Reformation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8rkOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA113|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1987|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|isbn=978-0-7102-1313-6|page=113}}</ref> He was at the [[University of Vienna]] 1384? to 1390;<ref>{{cite book|author=Annabel S. Brett|title=Liberty, Right and Nature: Individual Rights in Later Scholastic Thought|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dt2yRMI8HKMC&pg=PA31|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=16 October 2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-54340-8|page=31}}</ref> he drew up the statutes there in 1389, with [[Henry of Langenstein]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Hilde de Ridder-Symoens|title=A History of the University in Europe: Volume 1, Universities in the Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Z1VBEbF0HAC&pg=PA436|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=16 October 2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-54113-8|page=436}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''Tractatus de contractibus''<ref>{{cite book|author=Odd Langholm|title=The Legacy of Scholasticism in Economic Thought: Antecedents of Choice and Power|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sTMvElDGCo0C&pg=PA205|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=13 February 1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-62159-5|page=205}}</ref>\n\nAround 1374 he abridged the ''Sentences'' commentary of [[Adam Wodeham]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Basil Studer|title=History of Theology: The Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2o5V2GWlaFIC&pg=PA500|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=15 March 2008|publisher=Liturgical Press|isbn=978-0-8146-5916-8|page=500}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gabriel Biel]]  \n* [[John Major (philosopher)|John Mair]]  \n* [[Adam de Wodeham]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* \"[[:de:Heinrich Totting von Oyta|Heinrich Totting von Oyta]]\" at [[German Wikipedia]] {{Link language|de}}\n* [http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz29313.html \"Heinrich Totting von Oyta\"] at ''[[Deutsche Biographie]]'' {{Link language|de}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henry of Oyta}}\n[[Category:1330 births]]\n[[Category:1397 deaths]]\n[[Category:14th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:14th-century Latin writers]]\n[[Category:14th-century Roman Catholic theologians]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Medieval German theologians]]\n[[Category:People from Cloppenburg (district)]]\n[[Category:Scholastic philosophers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German theologian and philosopher}}\n'''Henry of Oyta''' ({{lang-de|Heinrich Totting von Oyta}}) (c.1330 \u2013 1397) was a German theologian and [[nominalist]] philosopher.\n\n==Life==\nHe was born at [[Friesoythe]] in [[Lower Saxony]].<ref>{{in lang|de}} [http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz29313.html deutsche-biographie.de, ''Heinrich Totting von Oyta''.]</ref>  \nHenry graduated M.A. at the [[Charles University in Prague|University of Prague]] in 1355. He was then rector of a school in [[Erfurt]], and returned to Prague in 1366.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mordechai Feingold|title=History of Universities: Volume XXI/1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=anGQ4QTBCX0C&pg=PA212|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=20 July 2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-929738-2|page=212}}</ref> In the course of a long-running dispute, Adalbert Ranconis accused him of heresy in 1369\u201370.<ref>{{cite book|author=Stefan Swie\u017cawski|title=Les tribulations de l'eccl\u00e9siologie \u00e0 la fin du Moyen Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fUPIAwgkLfwC&pg=PA17|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1997|publisher=Editions Beauchesne|isbn=978-2-7010-1351-0|page=17 note 64|language=fr}}</ref> He began teaching at the [[University of Paris]] in 1377.<ref name=\"Meyjes1999\">{{cite book|author=Guillaume Henri Marie Posthumus Meyjes|title=Jean Gerson, Apostle of Unity: His Church Politics and Ecclesiology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=64h0Y-lLB7AC&pg=PA323|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1999|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-11296-4|page=323}}</ref> For reasons connected with the [[Western Schism]], he left Paris in 1381;<ref>{{cite book|author=Guillaume Henri Marie Posthumus Meyjes|title=Jean Gerson, Apostle of Unity: His Church Politics and Ecclesiology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=64h0Y-lLB7AC&pg=PA22|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1999|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-11296-4|page=22}}</ref> he then taught at Prague, 1381 to 1381, lecturing there on the [[Psalms]] and [[Gospel of John]].<ref name=\"Meyjes1999\"/><ref>{{cite book|author1=Bernard McGinn|author2=John Meyendorff|title=Christian Spirituality: High Middle Ages and Reformation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8rkOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA113|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1987|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|isbn=978-0-7102-1313-6|page=113}}</ref> He was at the [[University of Vienna]] 1384? to 1390;<ref>{{cite book|author=Annabel S. Brett|title=Liberty, Right and Nature: Individual Rights in Later Scholastic Thought|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dt2yRMI8HKMC&pg=PA31|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=16 October 2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-54340-8|page=31}}</ref> he drew up the statutes there in 1389, with [[Henry of Langenstein]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Hilde de Ridder-Symoens|title=A History of the University in Europe: Volume 1, Universities in the Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Z1VBEbF0HAC&pg=PA436|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=16 October 2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-54113-8|page=436}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''Tractatus de contractibus''<ref>{{cite book|author=Odd Langholm|title=The Legacy of Scholasticism in Economic Thought: Antecedents of Choice and Power|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sTMvElDGCo0C&pg=PA205|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=13 February 1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-62159-5|page=205}}</ref>\n\nAround 1374 he abridged the ''Sentences'' commentary of [[Adam Wodeham]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Basil Studer|title=History of Theology: The Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2o5V2GWlaFIC&pg=PA500|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=15 March 2008|publisher=Liturgical Press|isbn=978-0-8146-5916-8|page=500}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gabriel Biel]]  \n* [[John Major (philosopher)|John Mair]]  \n* [[Adam de Wodeham]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* \"[[:de:Heinrich Totting von Oyta|Heinrich Totting von Oyta]]\" at German Wikipedia {{Link language|German}}\n* \"Heinrich Totting von Oyta\" [http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz29313.html] {{Link language|German}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henry of Oyta}}\n[[Category:1330 births]]\n[[Category:1397 deaths]]\n[[Category:14th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:14th-century Latin writers]]\n[[Category:14th-century Roman Catholic theologians]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Medieval German theologians]]\n[[Category:People from Cloppenburg (district)]]\n[[Category:Scholastic philosophers]]\n", "name_user": "DocWatson42", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Performed minor cleanup and wikification.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_of_Oyta"}
